Scottish hopes; Coulthard wants rain; lawyer fan quits;
Eds: ADDS items on death of referee Dienst; Laudrup-Schmeichel;
PARIS (AP) _ Gottfried Dienst, who controversially awarded England's third goal in the 1966 World Cup final with the Germans protesting the ball hadn't crossed the line, has died after a short illness. The Swiss referee's decision became part of World Cup history when Geoff Hurst's injury-time shot hit the underside of the crossbar, bounced down and out into play. English players celebrated a goal and the Germans ran to linesman Tofik Bakhramov to protest. Dienst ran to the linesman too, awarded the goal, England then led 3-2 and finally won 4-2. ___ COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) _ For two of Denmark's top players, Friday's friendly against Cameroon had something special: Michael Laudrup said farewell to his fans at home after 16 years on the team and Peter Schmeichel marked his 100th game in goal. Laudrup, who also played on Denmark's 1986 World Cup side in Mexico, announced in May he will retire from soccer at age 33 after the World Cup finals. Cheered by some 37,000 fans at the national Parken stadium in Copenhagen, a visibly moved Laudrup, making his 98th appearance, kicked off his last game on Danish soil while supporters chanted ``Michael, Michael.'' His professional career took him to European powerhouses like Juventus, Barcelona, Real Madrid and Ajax Amsterdam. One of the world's top keepers, Manchester United's Schmeichel is the second Dane to reach the magic figure. Of the 100 games, he has managed to keep the ball out of the net 46 times. Schmeichel and Laudrup likely will beat former international Morten Olsen's record of 102 games as both been selected for the World Cup. ___ GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) _ Like a fighter who's been knocked out in the first round seven times in a row, Scotland's soccer team will celebrate if they finally reach round two of the World Cup. ``We have a great chance to make history, and the boys know that. We have got to dispel the notion of being brave losers,'' coach Craig Brown said Friday as the team departed for France ahead of the June 10 opening game against defending titlist Brazil. ``We will really be at the highest level,'' he added. ``We are one of 30 teams who have qualified to join the hosts and holders. ``There are some 142 countries who have not made it, like Portugal and Sweden. We are there and viewed as one of the underdogs, which is fine by us.'' ___ MONTREAL, Canada (AP) _ Formula One star David Coulthard is likely to be the only driver who hopes next Wednesday's testing at Silverstone is rained off. The McLaren driver has a ticket for the World Cup opener between Brazil and his native Scotland. ``I have been exploring all the options to see how I can get there,'' said Coulthard, who is in Montreal for Sunday's Canadian Grand Prix. ``I have a group of friends who are going and they have got the tickets, but the problem is we are testing next week. We were due to test at Magny-Cours in France which would have made it easier. ``But it has been switched to Silverstone,'' Coulthard said. ``All I can hope now is that the test that day is called off because of rain.'' ___ WEST BROMWICH, England (AP) _ Lawyer Jonathan Finn has quit his job to spend a month in France watching the World Cup. The 32-year-old fan has gained tickets to 20 World Cup games and can't wait to get to the World Cup. ``The wine, the food, the culture, the scenery, the atmosphere among visiting supporters, the football itself - it was just all too much to miss,'' said Finn, who supports division one West Bromwich Albion. He managed to get hold of so many tickets after a friend had the brainwave to ring the ticket-line at 3 pm on Saturdays, while the lines were quiet because English fans were at matches. ___ MILAN, Italy (AP) _ Call it Ro-Ro, 1st graf
